cs.IT, cs.SP, cs.MM, cs.LG, cs.SI. 

The paper deals with signal processing and information theory, specifically with the problem of Basis Pursuit De-Noising (BPDN) in which the sparse original signal is drawn from a finite alphabet. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.SP (Signal Processing) are the most likely categories. The paper also discusses the use of a Rademacher measurement matrix and a measurement matrix derived from the random demodulator, which are related to compressive sensing and matrix multiplication, respectively, suggesting cs.MM (Mathematical Methods) as another possible category. The paper also introduces a prior distribution to capitalize on the discrete nature of the original signal, which is related to machine learning and probabilistic modeling, suggesting cs.LG (Machine Learning) as another possible category. Finally, the paper proposes an iterative message passing algorithm, which is a common technique in network science and communication systems, suggesting cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as another possible category.
